[8] Cholera - Laos: (Xekong)
Date: Wed 30 Jan 2008
Source: UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) [edited]
<http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/laopdr_42701.html>


The 1st outbreak of cholera in southern Lao People's Democratic Republic in
nearly 8 years has prompted a vigorous response from UNICEF and its
partners. UNICEF's response is in close coordination with the Lao Ministry
of Health, the World Health Organization (WHO), and the Asian Development Bank.

The epidemic was first recognized in the remote Xekong Province in late
December 2007. By mid-January 2008, it had spread to some 30 villages in
the Thataeng and Lamam Districts, where 362 cases of severe diarrhea were
reported, including 3 deaths.

"Now we are ensuring that people have access to safe drinking water,
latrines and boiled water, not just in the 2 affected districts of Xekong
Province but in all surrounding areas," said UNICEF's chief of Water,
Sanitation and Hygiene for Lao PDR, Abdulai Kaikai.

Mr Kaikai, who represented UNICEF on the initial joint assessment mission
to the area, commended the swift reaction of the government in dealing with
the crisis. On 11 Jan 2008, Lao PDR prime minister Bouasone Bouphavanh
visited Sekong to coordinate efforts to deal with the outbreak and meet
cholera patients.

Health experts are now hopeful that the outbreak has been contained. No
deaths have been reported since 3 Jan 2008. "The number of new cases has
dramatically dropped," said UNICEF's chief of Young Child Survival and
Development for Lao PDR, Dr Aboudou Karimou Andele. "This means people have
understood what to do to avoid infection."

[byline: Tom Greenwood]

--
communicated by:
